\begin_layout Chapter
The E08-027 (g2p) Experiment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The E08-027 (g2p) experiment studied the spin structure function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 by measuring the cross section of the inclusive electron-proton scattering.
 The experiment successfully collected data from March to May, 2012 in Hall
 A at Jefferson Lab.
 This chapter will go through the experiment in detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in the previous chapters, measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 needs more precise data than 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 JLab has been at the forefront for measuring the nucleon spin structure
 over the wide kinematic range in the latest decades.
 With the high luminosity and high polarization electron beam and the high
 precision equipment in all of three Halls, JLab has been completed a number
 of precise experiments, which extended the data on spin structure significantly
 on both kinematic ranges and the precision.
 The data of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 for neutron has been collected precisely in both DIS and resonance region
 for neutron in the previous experiments, but the data for proton in the
 resonance region is still lacking.
 Comparing with the DIS region, studying in the resonance region can reveal
 more information on the internal structure of nucleon resonances and their
 excitation, which is important to check the related theory, such as the
 chiral perturbative theory and the lattice QCD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 data can provide a test of the Burkhardt-Cottingham sum rule.
 Since the BC sum rule should apply at all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, it can be tested by either at DIS region or at low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 region.
 The data from the neutron shows agreement with the B-C sum rule, while
 the proton result from SLAC E155 shows large disagreement.
 Also a significant contribution to the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 integral comes from the nuclear resonance region.
 The precise 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 data from low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

is important to test the B-C sum rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A measurement of the longitudinal-transverse spin polarizability 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{LT}$
\end_inset

 is expected to be a good test for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

.
 The resent neutron result shows significant disagreement with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 calculation.
 However, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{LT}$
\end_inset

 for the proton at low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

does not exist yet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 data will help to improve the precision in the hyperfine splitting of the
 hydrogen ground state, since the leading uncertainty in the measurement
 of the hyperfine splitting in the hydrogen ground state comes from the
 proton structure correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.96.163001"

\end_inset

.
 The data from this experiment may also help to improve the precision of
 the measurement for the proton charge radius.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the E08-027 experiment is to measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 structure function for the proton at low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}.$
\end_inset

 A measurement of the scattered electrons in the reaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{p}(\overrightarrow{e},e')X$
\end_inset

 at a scattering-angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $5.69\textdegree$
\end_inset

 in the low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 region of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02<Q^{2}<0.2\,GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

 was performed to obtain the proton spin-dependent cross sections (see figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
